##10,000 PEOPLE IN THE PAVILION: a month after the banquet

To-cure-sometimes

The function introduces, records the person and the disease, the senility, the death coexistence way.

In Wuhan and even the whole country, the Baibu pavilion community is a benchmark type of existence. The community is located in the city of Jiang'an District in Wuhan, Hubei Province, and consists of 11 residential districts with a resident population of 130,000.

Baibu pavilion is divided into Anju Yuan, Baihe Yuan, Modern City, Jing Lan yuan, Yue Xiu Yuan, happy times and 11 other communities.
Image: A screenshot of Baidu maps

On January 18,2020, just two days before Academician Zhong Nanshan connected with CCTV to confirm that the new type of coronary pneumonia was "passed from one person to another" , the Baibu Pavilion Community hosted a family dinner for 10,000 people. According to Chutian metropolis daily on the 19th, "residents in the community served 13,866 dishes, bringing together more than 40,000 families. "

Related reports in Chutian metropolis daily
Image: screenshot

At that time, the shadow of the epidemic has been hanging over Wuhan. Held until the 20th year, the 10,000-person family dinner, which was once the community's business card, made the Baibu pavilion community the focus of public opinion because of the crowd.

On January 23, the fifth day after the banquet ended, Wuhan declared the city closed.

On February 4, the 16th day after the banquet, a news report in the The Economic Observer said that "fever patients were found in 33 of the 55 buildings" in a community under the Baibu pavilion community. On February 5, Caixin also reported that, fever patients found in multi-door buildings in Wuhan Baibu Pavilion Community.

Baibu pavilion was pushed to the top of the storm once again.

"The occasional cure" finds several residents who live in the Baibu pavilion community, combs through their lives and the problems they face, and tries to show the world in the shadow of the epidemic in this benchmark community.

Gossip and family dinners

Zhang, 60, has been attending community banquets and competing for awards since moving to Baibu pavilion in 2003. Except this year, because she's a Buddhist. Zhang Ning has been working as a volunteer in the North for the past year.

On December 30,2019, Zhang Ning received the news of his brother's death and rushed back to Wuhan.

On the same day, some people in Wuhan began circulating screenshots of several doctors suggesting that the SARS virus might be there. A related source said that an internal notice from the medical and Health Administration Department of Wuhan Health Commission said "pneumonia of unknown cause has occurred in Wuhan" and was related to the south China Seafood Wholesale Market.

Wang Qi, who has lived in the modern city of Baibu pavilion for 10 years, noticed the rumors on this very day.

On New Year's Eve, Wang Qi and his colleagues had dinner near the South China Seafood Wholesale Market. He and his colleagues also discussed how their off-campus training industry would be hard hit if SARS were to happen again.

On January 1, "Ping an Wuhan" posted on its microblog that eight people who had spread rumors had been dealt with according to law. Wang Qi did not receive the notice of suspension of classes, we are still normal work.

On January 18, Baibu Pavilion hosted the 20th annual "banquet for 10,000 people" . On the same day, the mother-in-law of Liu Lian, who lives in Baibu pavilion, went to attend.

Liu Lian and her family have lived in the garden for five years. Liu Lian did not send her children to kindergarten for the whole of December 2019 because of the flu.

In January, she also heard about pneumonia of unknown origin, so she kept the baby at home. Because the children at home with the school suspension, but also worried about the crowd gathered infected with the flu, Ten Thousand Family Feast That Day mother-in-law holding a disposable bowl filled with food, they went home. Wash your hands carefully before eating. Liu Lian said, "It's a good thing I brought it home that day. ". "

On January 19, Wang Qi came home from work to find a supply of face masks at the school's pharmacy, but found they were nearly sold out. The shop owner explained that they were already stocking up, so Wang Qi and his colleagues said to make a little bit of advance, just in case. Two people also did not buy more, think two bags are enough.

On January 20,136 new cases were confirmed in two days, according to the Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission. On the same night, when Academician Zhong Nanshan accepted the CCTV link, he made it clear that the COVID-19 was "from person to person. ".

Wang Qi began to realize the seriousness of the situation, but found that he could no longer buy masks. The two bags he bought yesterday were clearly not enough, so he sent a bag of N95 masks through his sister-in-law in Jiangxi, and another five bags of surgical masks from Nanjing.

On January 21,15 cases of infection were reported by Wuhan Municipal Health Commission and 72 new cases were reported by Hubei Provincial Health Commission.

One day, Liu Lian went to the daily necessities store to work as usual. Suddenly, a lot of people came to the store to buy masks. "

On January 22, Hubei Province launched the second-level emergency response to public emergencies.

On January 23rd, Wuhan was sealed off from 10 am. But Liu Lian did not receive the suspension notice, as usual went to the store.

At this time, the shop has been sold out of masks, someone bought all the remaining shop spray bottle, said it is used for alcohol disinfection.

In the afternoon, the store where Liu Lian worked closed.

The community is undefended

On Feb. 10, at a news conference in Hubei Province on the prevention and control of the COVID-19 infection, Ma Guoqiang, the former party secretary of Wuhan, said the city had launched a nationwide health survey, with 99 percent of the population screened.

February 13,100 Pavilion Community Expo Park Yu Tian finally received the first community call temperature screening. She said, "I'm not the one percent anymore. ".

Liu Lian, who lives in Jing Lan Yuan, has not received a temperature screening call before. It was not until February 15 that property workers rang the doorbell downstairs, asking Liu Lian's family, "how many people are there in the house? " "Is the temperature normal? ".

Compared with the late calls, Yu Tian's building has long been labeled a "hot building. ". After the closure of the city, Yu Tian answered the government's call and rarely went out. She did not even know when it was posted.

Yutian residential building door posted on the hot building
Photo: Courtesy of the respondents

Through the observation of the community staff door-to-door delivery and eliminate the track, Yu Tian confirmed the diagnosis of patients from their home incredibly close. "The neighbors were picked up around 10:00 p.m. on February 9, " she said. "

After the patient was picked up, the "fever building" logo still did not take down, she suspected that there are other fever patients in the building.

Yu Tian's family lives in another community under the Baibu Pavilion Group. In order to take care of the elderly, she moved with her children to her parents'home in the Expo Park, one stop away.

Ms. Yu said neither her parents'Expo Park nor her family's neighborhood had disclosed the location of the popular buildings, the number of confirmed and suspected patients in the neighborhood and how they were treated.

According to her, her parents-in-law live in a community in Wuchang, every day will be transparent about the situation in the community.

"Every day, their community publishes a grid of suspected patients who have been quarantined at home, and a grid of how many confirmed patients have been sent to a shelter or hospital for treatment, which is very standard. "

"You don't have to say which one, but at least you know what you're doing, " she said. "

The same is true of Wang Qi, who lives in the Baibu pavilion modern city. The community has yet to disclose how many confirmed patients there are, and the property has yet to disclose the grid of confirmed patients. Despite the owners in the group every day strong demand, but the property side has refused to open.

He noticed that the hot building in the community, also experienced from scratch, and then to no process.

The ambulance he saw from upstairs came four times. In addition, under the "Super Topic" of "pneumonia patients asking for help" on Weibo, Wang Qi saw three patients from his own community asking for help, hoping to be confirmed as soon as possible and to secure hospital beds.

An ambulance photographed by Wang Qi
Photo: Courtesy of the respondents

In addition, the community access management is also very loose. After the closure of the city, Wang Qi and other owners strongly require residential property in and out of the registration and temperature measurement.

On January 31, the property in modern city took a photo of its temperature and posted it to the owners'group; other owners reported, however, that strict entry and exit registration had not been implemented.
Emergency notice for Modern City community

Photo: Courtesy of the respondents

Since then, Wang Qi in the eighth day (February 1) , January 14(February 7) have been in and out of the community, but have not encountered staff on their own temperature measurement or staff registration.

The temperature readings sometimes went haywire until Feb. 13, the day before the new crown pneumonia epidemic prevention and control headquarters in Wuhan decided on the closure of residential areas, and the modern city under the Baibu pavilion began to strictly control access.

On that day, 35,991 cases and 7,492 critical cases were confirmed in Wuhan, 22 days after the city was sealed off.

The plight of the residents

Since the closure of the city, the daily life of the residents of the Baibu pavilion community has become difficult.

The day after the meal is over, Xiao Lan's husband, who lives in Baibu Pavilion, will leave the house at 8 a.m. and go to Zhongbai Supermarket, not far from home. In the beginning, everyone was in a huddle. Later, when they were standing in line, they were separated by about one meter.

8:00 Out, 12:00 home, her husband's hand-carried bag only grab the remaining ribs. "The line is two or three hours long. ". Chorin said.

Every morning at 8 am, online ordering platforms also start a rush of vegetables. "It'll be over in a minute. "said Chorin.

To ease the difficulty of buying food, community volunteers began to organize group orders of vegetables, so that the delivery person can deliver food to everyone at a fixed time and place. Later, because the community is too large, the delivery man did not feel cost-effective, but also worried about infection, things fall by the wayside.

Until Feb. 16, Chorin lived in an Ju Yuan began to organize a unified group purchase.

More troubling to the Liu Lians than shopping was the fact that she couldn't get the medicine.

Liu Lian and her mother-in-law are both type 2 diabetics. As usual, Liu Lian needed insulin injections three times a day. The type of insulin she uses is available only at the heart-to-heart pharmacy and Wuhan Central Hospital in Wuhan.

The head of Xinlianxin Pharmacy told her that they could not get in because of the road closure and traffic inconvenience. Liu Lian ran to the five nearby pharmacies, all empty. Liu called the Wuhan Central Hospital and was told that the Houhu hospital area near her home had been closed because of the outbreak, and that she could not get to the Jianghan Road Hospital area because of the closure. Also, the doctor who answered the phone advised not to come to the hospital except for severe cases, and going to the hospital would not necessarily lead to the prescription of medicine.

Liu Lian even asked a nurse she knew to buy some from the hospital, but still couldn't.

Liu Lian's insulin
Photo: Courtesy of the respondents

Last time I stocked up was before New Year's Eve. Now, she can only control her blood sugar by taking a day pill, keeping her mouth shut, and switching from three insulin injections a day to one. Instead of 70 units a day, she can get her blood sugar down to 30 units a day and keep it up for a while.

The shortage of medicine in Granny Liu is even more serious. Although her medicine is sold in most drugstores, the old man bought it in twos and threes. He couldn't get it when he went out last time, so he brought back the only two boxes of hypoglycemic medicine in the store.

Now, she has only one 300-unit dose of insulin left, whereas she would have had to inject 60 units a day, which is only enough for five days.

The Yutian family faces the same dilemma. Her parents were chronically ill, with high blood pressure, diabetes and coronary heart disease for more than a decade. In addition to conventional chronic medicine, Yu Tian's mother had just had eye surgery in November 2019 and needed a large amount of medication every day.

Now mother only has enough medicine for one day.

From February 14, the Wuhan community began to implement closed management. Community personnel see Yu Tian need to buy medicine is too complex, let her take medical records, identity cards can go out to buy.

Even if I could get out of the neighborhood, it wouldn't matter. She said, "the medicine is so tight right now, I don't know where to buy it. "

Huddle up for warmth

Zhang Ning has not been out of the Baibu pavilion since the city was closed, because there is no mask.

New Year's Eve, Zhang Ning received a message from her daughter, said the city of Wuhan closed, told her to buy some food. Zhang, unaware of the severity of the outbreak, bought only two potatoes, some cabbage and celery.

These dishes barely lasted until the seventh day of the Lunar New Year. Daughter and in-laws living outside the community, called to say to send food. Zhang Ning worried about her daughter infection, they cheated her to eat, let her not come over.

Neighbors Know Zhang Ning live alone, and no mask, they actively asked her if there are dishes; learned that directly in wechat mission two dishes, and bought two bags of noodles.

The food arrived at 12 o'clock in the evening. The neighbors brought it back together and sent it directly to Zhang Ning's house without asking for money.

"If it hadn't been for the young people in my neighborhood buying me food, I would have starved to death, " Zhang said. "I couldn't go out without food. "

"It's an exaggeration to die of hunger, but it's true to have no food, " she added.

After the vegetable, property staff have called to contact her whether there is a problem, she thought it has been resolved, then did not mention.

Zhang Ning has always loved the habit of hiding things, no mask can not go out, in the home, finally in a ball of newspaper found a few years ago gauze mask and disposable mask.

When she goes out to take out the trash, she stacks the two masks together. When you get home, hang two masks on the balcony for ventilation and use them again.

Wang Qi's family in modern city has plenty of food and supplies, but according to group chats, some elderly people in the community can not solve the problem of living materials, so they formed some group purchase groups with other owners.

After organizing the first group purchase of alcohol on February 1, the owners of modern city each looked for sources through different channels, made a group purchase together to buy vegetables, and elected responsible persons in different buildings to be responsible for the distribution of dishes.

"If anyone has a channel to buy food, send it to the group that buys it. The building director is responsible for collecting notices and receipts, and so on the food to inform the residents in batches down to take food. "

Food and distribution in zone 2 of modern city
Photo: Courtesy of the respondents

Wang said that the group purchase of dishes in modern city has always been the responsibility of the owners, who have repeatedly called the property and neighborhood committees, hoping that they can come forward to organize, to be more convenient in the supply negotiations.

"when the food arrived, the vendors left, and the owners kept watch downstairs. "

He said, "The pavilion is a little scary. "

Between Wang Qi and the owner of the self-printed paper, posted on the elevator, to distinguish between heating elevator and non-heating Elevator, reduce the risk of cross-infection. The owner also once proposed with the property, but always has no one to carry out, can only do by oneself.

February 16, the 25th day of the city, Modern City finally by the neighborhood began to organize group purchase of food issues.

10,000 dinners a month

On Feb. 18, it was 26 days since Hubei Province launched its first level response to a major public health emergency, 27 days since the city was shut down in Wuhan, a full month since the banquets, and 50 days since Wang Qi first heard about the unknown virus.

Wang did not know if his off-campus training company would survive the outbreak.

For now, Wang and his colleagues are preparing for classes every day, moving as much as they can online, and completing the hours of teaching that they were promised. Money is the biggest problem. Now the account has enough money for two months, Wang Qi and several shareholders began to discuss fundraising, trying to maintain until the resumption of work.

Zhang Ning got rid of the situation without a mask, and the mask sent to her by her classmates finally arrived. After keeping some for herself, she gave some of the masks to neighbors and property workers.

The Mask Zhang Ning received
Photo: Courtesy of the respondents

On February 12, Yu Tian went downstairs to get a delivery, and heard someone screaming through the window in the building next door.

The property was tight, but it turned out to be no big deal. You know, when you're locked up for too long, you want to blow off some steam. "

If I could, I'd give it a shout. "She added.

Yu Tian husband failed to rush back to Wuhan, remaining in another city in Hubei Isolation.

She said she hoped the outbreak would end soon and she would be reunited with her husband, where she could buy a fresh fish and have a family reunion dinner.

To protect the privacy of interviewees, Liu Lian, Zhang Ning, Wang Qi, Chorin and Yu Tian are pseudonyms

In addition, the community access management is also very loose. After the closure of the city, Wang Qi and other owners strongly require residential property in and out of the registration and temperature measurement.

On January 31, the property in modern city took a photo of its temperature and posted it to the owners'group; other owners reported, however, that strict entry and exit registration had not been implemented.
Emergency notice for Modern City community

Photo: Courtesy of the respondents

Since then, Wang Qi in the eighth day (February 1) , January 14(February 7) have been in and out of the community, but have not encountered staff on their own temperature measurement or staff registration.

The temperature readings sometimes went haywire until Feb. 13, the day before the new crown pneumonia epidemic prevention and control headquarters in Wuhan decided on the closure of residential areas, and the modern city under the Baibu pavilion began to strictly control access.

On that day, 35,991 cases and 7,492 critical cases were confirmed in Wuhan, 22 days after the city was sealed off.

On Feb. 10, at a news conference in Hubei Province on the prevention and control of the COVID-19 infection, Ma Guoqiang, the former party secretary of Wuhan, said the city had launched a nationwide health survey, with 99 percent of the population screened.

February 13,100 Pavilion Community Expo Park Yu Tian finally received the first community call temperature screening. She said, "I'm not the one percent anymore. ".

Liu Lian, who lives in Jing Lan Yuan, has not received a temperature screening call before. It was not until February 15 that property workers rang the doorbell downstairs, asking Liu Lian's family, "how many people are there in the house? " "Is the temperature normal? ".

Compared with the late calls, Yu Tian's building has long been labeled a "hot building. ". After the closure of the city, Yu Tian answered the government's call and rarely went out. She did not even know when it was posted.

Yutian residential building door posted on the hot building

Yutian residential building door posted on the hot building

Photo: Courtesy of the respondents

Through the observation of the community staff door-to-door delivery and eliminate the track, Yu Tian confirmed the diagnosis of patients from their home incredibly close. "The neighbors were picked up around 10:00 p.m. on February 9, " she said. "

After the patient was picked up, the "fever building" logo still did not take down, she suspected that there are other fever patients in the building.

Yu Tian's family lives in another community under the Baibu Pavilion Group. In order to take care of the elderly, she moved with her children to her parents'home in the Expo Park, one stop away.

Ms. Yu said neither her parents'Expo Park nor her family's neighborhood had disclosed the location of the popular buildings, the number of confirmed and suspected patients in the neighborhood and how they were treated.

According to her, her parents-in-law live in a community in Wuchang, every day will be transparent about the situation in the community.

"Every day, their community publishes a grid of suspected patients who have been quarantined at home, and a grid of how many confirmed patients have been sent to a shelter or hospital for treatment, which is very standard. "

"You don't have to say which one, but at least you know what you're doing, " she said. "

The same is true of Wang Qi, who lives in the Baibu pavilion modern city. The community has yet to disclose how many confirmed patients there are, and the property has yet to disclose the grid of confirmed patients. Despite the owners in the group every day strong demand, but the property side has refused to open.

He noticed that the hot building in the community, also experienced from scratch, and then to no process.

The plight of the residents

Since the closure of the city, the daily life of the residents of the Baibu pavilion community has become difficult.

The day after the meal is over, Xiao Lan's husband, who lives in Baibu Pavilion, will leave the house at 8 a.m. and go to Zhongbai Supermarket, not far from home. In the beginning, everyone was in a huddle. Later, when they were standing in line, they were separated by about one meter.

8:00 Out, 12:00 home, her husband's hand-carried bag only grab the remaining ribs. "The line is two or three hours long. ". Chorin said.

Every morning at 8 am, online ordering platforms also start a rush of vegetables. "It'll be over in a minute. "said Chorin.

To ease the difficulty of buying food, community volunteers began to organize group orders of vegetables, so that the delivery person can deliver food to everyone at a fixed time and place. Later, because the community is too large, the delivery man did not feel cost-effective, but also worried about infection, things fall by the wayside.

Until Feb. 16, Chorin lived in an Ju Yuan began to organize a unified group purchase.

More troubling to the Liu Lians than shopping was the fact that she couldn't get the medicine.

Liu Lian and her mother-in-law are both type 2 diabetics. As usual, Liu Lian needed insulin injections three times a day. The type of insulin she uses is available only at the heart-to-heart pharmacy and Wuhan Central Hospital in Wuhan.

The head of Xinlianxin Pharmacy told her that they could not get in because of the road closure and traffic inconvenience. Liu Lian ran to the five nearby pharmacies, all empty. Liu called the Wuhan Central Hospital and was told that the Houhu hospital area near her home had been closed because of the outbreak, and that she could not get to the Jianghan Road Hospital area because of the closure. Also, the doctor who answered the phone advised not to come to the hospital except for severe cases, and going to the hospital would not necessarily lead to the prescription of medicine.

Liu Lian even asked a nurse she knew to buy some from the hospital, but still couldn't.

Liu Lian's insulin
Photo: Courtesy of the respondents

Last time I stocked up was before New Year's Eve. Now, she can only control her blood sugar by taking a day pill, keeping her mouth shut, and switching from three insulin injections a day to one. Instead of 70 units a day, she can get her blood sugar down to 30 units a day and keep it up for a while.

The shortage of medicine in Granny Liu is even more serious. Although her medicine is sold in most drugstores, the old man bought it in twos and threes. He couldn't get it when he went out last time, so he brought back the only two boxes of hypoglycemic medicine in the store.

Now, she has only one 300-unit dose of insulin left, whereas she would have had to inject 60 units a day, which is only enough for five days.

The Yutian family faces the same dilemma. Her parents were chronically ill, with high blood pressure, diabetes and coronary heart disease for more than a decade. In addition to conventional chronic medicine, Yu Tian's mother had just had eye surgery in November 2019 and needed a large amount of medication every day.

Now mother only has enough medicine for one day.

From February 14, the Wuhan community began to implement closed management. Community personnel see Yu Tian need to buy medicine is too complex, let her take medical records, identity cards can go out to buy.

Even if I could get out of the neighborhood, it wouldn't matter. She said, "the medicine is so tight right now, I don't know where to buy it. "

Huddle up for warmth

Zhang Ning has not been out of the Baibu pavilion since the city was closed, because there is no mask.

New Year's Eve, Zhang Ning received a message from her daughter, said the city of Wuhan closed, told her to buy some food. Zhang, unaware of the severity of the outbreak, bought only two potatoes, some cabbage and celery.

These dishes barely lasted until the seventh day of the Lunar New Year. Daughter and in-laws living outside the community, called to say to send food. Zhang Ning worried about her daughter infection, they cheated her to eat, let her not come over.

Neighbors Know Zhang Ning live alone, and no mask, they actively asked her if there are dishes; learned that directly in wechat mission two dishes, and bought two bags of noodles.

The food arrived at 12 o'clock in the evening. The neighbors brought it back together and sent it directly to Zhang Ning's house without asking for money.

"If it hadn't been for the young people in my neighborhood buying me food, I would have starved to death, " Zhang said. "I couldn't go out without food. "

"It's an exaggeration to die of hunger, but it's true to have no food, " she added.

After the vegetable, property staff have called to contact her whether there is a problem, she thought it has been resolved, then did not mention.

Zhang Ning has always loved the habit of hiding things, no mask can not go out, in the home, finally in a ball of newspaper found a few years ago gauze mask and disposable mask.

When she goes out to take out the trash, she stacks the two masks together. When you get home, hang two masks on the balcony for ventilation and use them again.

Wang Qi's family in modern city has plenty of food and supplies, but according to group chats, some elderly people in the community can not solve the problem of living materials, so they formed some group purchase groups with other owners.

After organizing the first group purchase of alcohol on February 1, the owners of modern city each looked for sources through different channels, made a group purchase together to buy vegetables, and elected responsible persons in different buildings to be responsible for the distribution of dishes.

"If anyone has a channel to buy food, send it to the group that buys it. The building director is responsible for collecting notices and receipts, and so on the food to inform the residents in batches down to take food. "

Food and distribution in zone 2 of modern city
Photo: Courtesy of the respondents

Wang said that the group purchase of dishes in modern city has always been the responsibility of the owners, who have repeatedly called the property and neighborhood committees, hoping that they can come forward to organize, to be more convenient in the supply negotiations.

"when the food arrived, the vendors left, and the owners kept watch downstairs. "

He said, "The pavilion is a little scary. "

Between Wang Qi and the owner of the self-printed paper, posted on the elevator, to distinguish between heating elevator and non-heating Elevator, reduce the risk of cross-infection. The owner also once proposed with the property, but always has no one to carry out, can only do by oneself.

February 16, the 25th day of the city, Modern City finally by the neighborhood began to organize group purchase of food issues.

10,000 dinners a month

On Feb. 18, it was 26 days since Hubei Province launched its first level response to a major public health emergency, 27 days since the city was shut down in Wuhan, a full month since the banquets, and 50 days since Wang Qi first heard about the unknown virus.

Wang did not know if his off-campus training company would survive the outbreak.

For now, Wang and his colleagues are preparing for classes every day, moving as much as they can online, and completing the hours of teaching that they were promised. Money is the biggest problem. Now the account has enough money for two months, Wang Qi and several shareholders began to discuss fundraising, trying to maintain until the resumption of work.

Zhang Ning got rid of the situation without a mask, and the mask sent to her by her classmates finally arrived. After keeping some for herself, she gave some of the masks to neighbors and property workers.

The property was tight, but it turned out to be no big deal. You know, when you're locked up for too long, you want to blow off some steam. "

If I could, I'd give it a shout. "She added.

Yu Tian husband failed to rush back to Wuhan, remaining in another city in Hubei Isolation.

She said she hoped the outbreak would end soon and she would be reunited with her husband, where she could buy a fresh fish and have a family reunion dinner.
